===Etymology===
{{back-form|en}} of singular form from plural {{m|en|seraphim}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|seraphim}}, from {{etyl|he|en}} {{m|he|שרפים|tr=serafim|sc=Hebr}}, plural form of {{m|he|שרף|tr=saraf|sc=Hebr}}. The plural "seraphims" occurs in the King James Bible (Isaiah chapter 6).

According to the Oxford English Dictionary, the singular "seraph" may have originated with [[w:John Milton|John Milton]] who used it in Book I of [[w:Paradise Lost|Paradise Lost]] (1667).

